{{Infobox language family |name=Bagirmi |region=[[Chad]] |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Central Sudanic]] |fam3=[[Bongo–Bagirmi languages|Bongo–Bagirmi]] |glotto=bagi1248 |glottorefname=Bagirmic }}
The '''Bagirmi languages''' comprise half a dozen languages spoken in southern [[Chad]]. They are members of the [[Central Sudanic languages|Central Sudanic]] language family.
The most populous Bagirmi language is [[Naba language|Naba]], spoken by the [[Bilala people|Bilala]], [[Kuka people|Kuka]], and [[Medogo people|Medogo]], who together number a quarter million. The languages are: :[[Bagirmi language|Barma]] (Bagirmi proper), [[Naba language|Naba]], [[Kenga language|Kenga]], [[Fer language|Fer]], [[Beraku language|Beraku]], [[Disa language|Disa]]
''Ethnologue'' lists a couple more ([[Jaya language|Jaya]], [[Morom language|Morom]]) between Kenga and Naba, and [[Gula language (Chad)|Gula]] (Sara Gula) further south, next to [[Sar language|Sar]].
