{{expand language|topic=|langcode=ko|otherarticle=문화어|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox East Asian name | koreanname = North Korean name | hangul = 문화어 | hanja = 文化語 | context = north | rr = Munhwaeo | mr = Munhwaŏ | koreanipa = | koreanname2 = South Korean name | hangul2 = 북한어 | hanja2 = 北韓語 | rr2 = Bukhaneo | mr2 = Puk'anŏ }} {{Other uses|Munhwa (disambiguation){{!}}Munhwa}} '''North Korean standard language''' or '''Munhwaŏ''' ({{korean |hangul=문화어 |hanja={{lang|ko|文化語}}|context=north}}) is the [[North Korea]]n [[standard language|standard version]] of [[Korean language]]. Munhwaŏ was adopted as the standard in 1966. The adopting proclamation stated that the [[Pyongan dialect]] spoken in the North Korean capital [[Pyongyang]] and its surroundings should be the basis for Munhwaŏ; however, in practice, Iksop Lee and S. Robert Ramsey report that Munhwaŏ remains "firmly rooted" in the [[Seoul dialect]], which had been the national standard for centuries. Most [[North–South differences in the Korean language|differences between the North and South Korean standards]] are thus attributable to replacement of [[Sino-Korean vocabulary]] and other [[loanword]]s with pure Korean words, or the Northern ideological preference for "the speech of the working class" which includes some words considered non-standard in the South.<ref name="LeeRamsey2000">{{cite book|author1=Iksop Lee|author2=S. Robert Ramsey|title=The Korean Language|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NN-yIdLOkCoC&pg=PA309|year=2000|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-4831-1|page=309}}</ref>
== Background == Following the liberation of Korea in 1945, both sides of the Korean peninsula continued to follow the Korean language guidelines as defined by the [[Korean Language Society]] in 1933 with the "Proposal for Unified Korean Orthography" ({{Ko-hhrm||||hangul=한글 맞춤법 통일안|hanja=|mr=|rr=}}) and in 1936 with the "Collection of Assessed Standard Korean Words" ({{Ko-hhrm||||hangul=사정한 조선어 표준말 모음|hanja=|mr=|rr=}}). In 1954, the 1933 proposal was replaced by a new system ({{Korean|hangul=조선어 철자법|hanja=|rr=|mr=|context=north}}) by the North Korean government in which thirteen words were slightly modified. Although the reformation created little difference, from this point the languages spoken by people on both sides on the Korean peninsula only grew in difference.
During the emergence of the [[Juche]] idea in the 1960s, [[Kim Il-sung]] coordinated an effort to purify the Korean language from [[English language|English]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], and [[Russian language|Russian]] loanwords as well as words with less common [[Hanja]] characters, replacing them with new words derived from native Korean words.
Thus, North Korea began to refer to its own dialect as "cultural language" ({{Korean|hangul=문화어|hanja=|rr=|mr=|context=north}}) as a reference to its return to words of Korean cultural origin, in juxtaposition to South Korea's reference to its own dialect as "standard language" ({{Korean|hangul=표준어|hanja=|rr=|mr=}}).
