{{Infobox writer | name = Richard Sapir | image = | image_size = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1936|7|27}} | birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States | death_date = {{death date and age|1987|1|27|1936|7|27}} | death_place = [[New Hampshire]], United States | occupation = Writer | nationality = American | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''[[The Destroyer (novel series)|The Destroyer]]'' | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = | portaldisp = }}
'''Richard Ben Sapir''' ({{IPAc-en|s|ə|ˈ|p|ɪər}}; 1936–1987) is best known for ''[[The Destroyer (fiction)|The Destroyer]]'' series of novels that he co-created with [[Warren Murphy]].<ref>Richard Sapir, & Warren Murphy (1985). ''Remo The Adventure Begins'', New York, NY: Signet.</ref><ref>M. C. Murphy (1995). ''The Destroyer # 100 Last Rites'', Ontario, Canada: Worldwide Library.</ref><ref>Richard Sapir, & Warren Murphy (1981). ''The Destroyer # 44 Balance of Power'', New York, NY: Pinnacle Books.</ref><ref>[http://ebooks.palm.com/author/detail/1111 Author Biography] viewed June 8, 2006.</ref><ref>Warren Murphy biography appended to body of work agreement (June 30, 2000) [http://sec.edgar-online.com/2000/06/30/17/0000932214-00-000120/Section28.asp Sec.edgar-online.com]</ref><ref>[http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/sapir_richard_ben Sf-encyclopedia.com]</ref>
The first ''Destroyer'' was written in 1963, while Sapir worked as a city hall reporter in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]] and Murphy served as secretary to the city's mayor. Ahead of its time with a plot centered upon a brash young westerner trained in the martial arts by a master assassin from [[North Korea]], the book went unpublished until June 1971 but eventually spawned a highly successful adventure series with over 30 million copies in print by the late 1990s.
Before arriving on the illustrious shores of [[Sinanju]], Sapir worked as an editor and in public relations. In addition to ''The Destroyer'' series, Sapir wrote five novels: ''Bressio'' (1975), ''[[The Far Arena]]'' (1978), ''[[The Body (novel)|The Body]]'' (1983), ''Spies'' (1984), and ''Quest'' (1987), a modern-day search for the Holy Grail. ''The Body'', which was made into a movie in 2001, is about a Jewish archaeologist who finds a skeleton underneath an Arab shopkeeper's basement that might be the body of Jesus and the American Jesuit priest who is sent by the Vatican to investigate.
Richard Sapir was a graduate of [[Columbia University]] and lived with his wife in [[New Hampshire]] before he died in 1987 from a heart attack.
