The '''Momuna languages''', [[Momina language|Momina]] and [[Momuna language|Momuna]], also known as '''Somahai''', are a [[language family|family]] of two closely related [[Papuan languages]]. 

==Classification==
The Somahai pronouns, singular *na, *ka, *mo, are typical of [[Trans–New Guinea]] languages. They were placed in the [[Central and South New Guinea languages|Central and South New Guinea]] branch of that family by Wurm. [[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Ross]] could not locate enough evidence to classify them. Usher found them to be closest to the [[Mek languages]], in the [[Central West New Guinea languages|Central West New Guinea]], which partially overlaps with Wurm's C&SNG.

